{
  "doc_id": "4484",
  "text": "Convergent evolution is the development of similar traits in different evolutionary lineages. Famous examples of convergence are the similar body forms and lifestyles of marsupial and eutherian mammals, camera eyes in vertebrates and cephalopods, and electrogeneration (and perception) in the platypus and in a number of fishes, but myriad evolutionary convergences have been discovered in molecules, physiological traits and complex morphological adaptations [CITATION_1] . The haemoglobins in animals, plants, protists and prokaryotes probably have an independent evolutionary origin [CITATION_2] , echolocation call design evolved convergently in bats [CITATION_3] and eusociality evolved convergently in insects, shrimps and mammals [CITATION_4] . However, despite the large number of observed cases of convergent evolution, its importance and implications are subjects of intense debate.",
